		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Haakon's Tourney Guide (For Laymen)<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.70)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=7216'>Haakon "[prototype]" Neinhalt-Schmutzig</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=7216&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 4, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> So you want to kickstart your career as a LOTR (or any other cardgame) professional, even though you&#8217;re just a scrub with a starter deck?<br />
<br />
I decided to write an article for those beginners(or even intermediate) players who just cant seem to get their leg up to the next level (not like THAT you sickos) of gameplay. There are a myriad of different ways a player can attempt to build on their skill base for LOTR, and they will find that the aptitude carries onto whatever other game they choose to play.<br />
<br />
Regardless of each player&#8217;s exposure to the game, I discovered in my area that players who previously were involved with MtG, SWCCG or any other cardgame (and were proficient) performed better overall than others, showing that it is a cardgame &#8216;knack&#8217; that beginners need to develop in order to be considered a threat.<br />
<br />
1] Preparation<br />
Let&#8217;s begin at home. I have read a whole load of tournament reports, both LOTR and SWCCG, and I cant count the number of people who do not describe their pre-tournament preparation. This, naturally, is an important skill to build on: without any experience in street combat, how do you expect to cop a punch from an attacker? Similarly, you cannot expect to compete without some preparation. Practice makes perfect. Same old cliché.<br />
<br />
When you construct your deck, add everything you possibly could think of that would help in some way or the other. Like the benefits both Aragorn and Gimli offer you? Chuck them both in for now. How about 3 swords so Aragorn is up and ready quickly? Put them in. You should end up with a broken wrist when you try to shuffle your deck. Now, lay out each card by type on the floor, and slowly consider the pro&#8217;s and con&#8217;s of each: how vital is this to my strategy? Do I really need Enduring Evil in a Sauron deck relying on direct damage? Does Gimli complement Aragorn as well as Arwen does? This is where a player&#8217;s &#8216;cumulative card knowledge&#8217; comes in handy, by which I mean that a player can recognise strategy and begin to filter out cards that do nothing. It is always worth having a second opinion present when you do this, so you have a couple of facets to look at:<br />
<br />
example1: Morgul Gates. Is this card so fantastic? Lets you play a nazgul at twilight cost &#8211;2. Whats the use if you cant draw a nazgul, or the cost is too expensive even if you have one? Potentially, this card is dead weight in your hand, combined with the fact that it&#8217;s a once off bonus might cause you to rethink using it, perhaps not with straight nazgul, but in a Sauron/Ringwraith hybrid (for argument&#8217;s sake).<br />
<br />
After this level of card culling, the next level is the question of how many copies of each to include. At this stage, you are weighting your cards in order of probability, and thus importance to your overall strategy. You kick off with Gimli and Legolas, but you&#8217;re a Gandalf player? 4 copies straight off the bat. The Pale Blade is a wicked sword, but can you really see yourself using more than 2? Especially since you&#8217;re running 2 Witch-Kings? Not good odds.<br />
Also keep in mind your total deck size. Its like fractions, remember those, kids? 2 copies of the Cavetroll in a deck is 2 out of 60 cards. Your odds are 1/30 of pulling one from your deck. However, say theres some more sweet goblins you want to throw in, and you increase your decksize to 70. You have just decreased your odds of the Cavetroll by the amount you increased your deck by. If you rely on the big guy for a beatdown at site 5 or 6 or something, you&#8217;d better rethink your card choices.<br />
<br />
Now you&#8217;ve tuned your deck a little&#8230;..<br />
<br />
2] Playtesting<br />
If you&#8217;re an arcade game player oeasterlingame like King of Fighters 2001, you will know that beating the computer aint no thang. Its when you match up against the Taiwanese guy with blonde hair, shiny jeans and a cord on his mobile phone that you recognise a true test of your skill. Its like that with cards, some decks look wicked cool on paper: maybe you dream about a Durin&#8217;s Secret deck with like&#8230;9 companions and heaps of allies, with Boat of the Galadrim and other stuff to run like crazy (no crap, some guy from geelong reckoned this would own people). Alright, you build this 1000 card pile and play against your mate&#8217;s Uruk deck who rip you to shreds cause you didn&#8217;t have space for support cards. It just isn&#8217;t feasible.<br />
<br />
The point remains that playtesting is the decider of your mettle. With your mates, you have a fishbowl bloodbath arena in which you can bludgeon the daylights out of each other in a quiet, peaceful setting, away from the torments of tournament pressure. Frequently you will find your playtester has either a wicked new idea that could confuse opponents, or he is playing a touchstone deck; something tried, true and solid as my 12 inch boner that you need practice against.<br />
<br />
However, not all playtesting is a positive experience for an impressionable newbie. Pick very carefully your buddies whom you have games with. Preferably mix with the more experienced guys, ask for tips and tricks, tell them what you think and get their opinion, call them over for a game, some coffee and cake. The more social you are with your playtesters, the more likely you are to receive positive attitudes during your sessions.<br />
<br />
Which brings me to the next point&#8230;.<br />
<br />
3] Attitude<br />
I cannot stress this point enough. This point is the maker or breaker oeasterlingood player&#8230;even the most dedicated cardboardphiles will crash and burn because of their attitude.<br />
<br />
A bit of high-school psychology (or even Freud For Dummies) will enable you to recognise the fundamental characteristics of your fellow humans. Perhaps X is a little too overconfident for his own good, and you note the way he buffs up one super companion, just waiting for the 2 Hates in your hand, and the Bowmen on the table. Perhaps Y gets angry really easily, and is disheartened by taking hurt (say, a rush of baddies who swamp a companion), rather than seeing you run ahead quickly. If you playtest with these sorts of people, you can expect their attitudes to rub off onto you if you communicate extensively with them. As good ol Confrimbazelious said (no, he really did), whenever you meet someone, you should engage in self reflection and appreciate the good, while rejecting the bad. As a rule, keep all your conflict on the table, and take none of it out socially. <br />
<br />
4] Tournament Mindset<br />
This point governs the way you perceive the game ability of other players. Knowing what you can/cannot get away with will win you a game or two. <br />
<br />
As a general guide, when you rock up to a tournament, subconsciously peghole the players you see as either movie fans, or cardplayers. Cardplayers are what you are here for: a challenge. Fanboys, however, are a different story. These people can lose sight of the fact that you are playing LOTR:TCG not LOTR the movie. You can walk all over these people, because they saw Gandalf die at the bridge in the film, and only Frodo and Sam make it to Tol Brandir. <br />
<br />
Check out the folders and trades to see what people have to offer. Subconsciously make a note of the guy with 9 Boromirs on his front page, and consider the potential threat of mains and toys you may face when you play against him. Similarly, look at the guy with uncommons and 1 or 2 minor rares in his file, and think of the kind of deck he may possibly have in store with his limited cardpool.<br />
<br />
Again, examine the dispositions of the people you play against. Against an arrogant player, just shake your head at the end of your shadow turn, ditch a FP card and say go, then bring down Uruks aplenty with a weather condition or two to end the game. Against a coward or incensed player, attack mercilessly with shadow and cause fear/anger, which then will affect the way they play their fellowship side. You get the idea. Simply play to the personal weaknesses of your opponents, and you have an instant advantage.<br />
<br />
Always, be polite, thank your opponent for the game, perhaps offer some token advice to a new player, and ask for some when you play a champ.<br />
<br />
That&#8217;s about all I had to say, I hope it was detailed enough to be of some help to you, reader. If there&#8217;s anything you think I could pick up on in a future article, please d-mail me for a chat.<br />
<br />
Play hard and have fun,<br />
Giles<br />
<br />
PS: I basically wrote this to get back in the swing of writing essays for English, so any Lit teachers out there, give me a letter grade in your review :)<br />
